        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Innes.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have got to go out &amp; do not wish to miss a Post, so write in great Hurry, to say that we shall be delighted to have Quiz, who shall be taken great care of, &amp; never parted with &amp; when old &amp; infirm shall pass from this life easily.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Most truly yours | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The dog ‘Quiz’ belonged to Innes’s son, John William (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3347.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Innes, 19 December [1861]</ref>). Innes, who had served as the perpetual curate of Down since 1846, had inherited the ancestral family home, Milton Brodie, in Forres, Scotland (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2662.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1978</ref>, p. 172, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5565.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Moore 1985</ref>, p. 469). After moving to Scotland, he assumed the name Brodie Innes.</note>
        </div>        
            
